FWIW I am always in favor of providing as many metrics as possible, explaining their benefits and drawbacks (e.g., through a user guide or example), and then letting users choose which ones they care about. IMO the downstream harms are the most important, so we should really be looking at the fairness metrics for the whole system (not just the preprocessing step). Having a few specific ones for preprocessing doesn't hurt, of course, but we shouldn't get into the habit of thinking that it's sufficient to minimize the max reconstruction error of all groups (to mention one particular metric).

I'd definitely consider creating a very small example (you can check the existing ones in case one of those suits you) where you apply "normal" PCA, `CorrelationRemover`, and then subsequently the other techniques as you add them. Then you can measure these new metrics as well as the downstream effects on fairness metrics.

